<div id="aueditable"><!--DO NOT MODIFY THIS LINE AND ABOVE-->

<h1>Numenius</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Mon May 4, 2009; substantive revision Tue Oct 1, 2024</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
Numenius, a Platonist philosopher of the mid 2<sup>nd</sup> century
CE, had considerable impact on later Platonism, most notably on
Plotinus (3<sup>rd</sup> c.) and Porphyry
(3<sup>rd</sup>-4<sup>th</sup> c). His work, surviving only in
fragments, is important both historically and philosophically. Its
historical significance lies mainly in that it shows how much of
Plotinus&rsquo; philosophy, especially Plotinus&rsquo; metaphysics,
was inspired by earlier Platonists such as Numenius, who was one of
the authors read in Plotinus&rsquo; seminar (Porphyry, <em>Life of
Plotinus</em> 14.12). Plotinus&rsquo; debt to Numenius&rsquo;
philosophy was much debated already by Platonists of Plotinus&rsquo;
generation (ibid. 18.2&ndash;3, 17.1&ndash;23). This discussion shows
that Plotinus was not considered in his own time to have initiated a
new and distinct movement in Platonism&mdash;what we today call
Neoplatonism. He was rather seen as simply continuing and developing
the philosophy of previous Platonists, Numenius being prominent among
them, just as they themselves had developed in similar fashion the
work of their own Platonist predecessors. Numenius&rsquo; significance
also lies in his impact on the thought of early Christian thinkers
like Origen and Eusebius, who were captured by Numenius&rsquo;
references to Hebrews as an ancient source of true doctrines (see
below Numenius&rsquo; Platonism) and saw in his doctrine of three gods
a prefiguration of the Christian trinitarian doctrine.</p>

<p>
Philosophically, Numenius&rsquo; work is important because he, like
Eudorus and Moderatus (1<sup>st</sup> c. CE), tried to construct a
hierarchical system of intelligible principles (<em>archai</em>) of
reality, but unlike them he held that intelligible principles are
responsible only for the order of the world, wherein its goodness
lies, while matter has an existence independent of these principles
and accounts for disorder and badness. In this sense Numenius
maintains a dualism in metaphysics that has affinities with that of
Plutarch but also with that of the Chaldean Oracles. Numenius&rsquo;
system of three principles of reality, similar to Plotinus&rsquo;
hypostases of One, Intellect and Soul, was constructed on the basis of
accounts of the intelligible world and its primacy, and of the soul as
a spiritual substance essentially related to that world, in Plato.
More specifically, it results from reflection on and interpretation of
the Form of the Good in <em>Republic</em> VI, the demiurge and the
world-soul of the <em>Timaeus</em>, and the One of the
<em>Parmenides</em>. The hierarchical order of these principles of
reality is determined by the degree of unity and simplicity of each;
the highest principle is the simplest and most completely a unity. It
is also absolutely good and transmits goodness.</p>

<p>
The reconstruction of Numenius&rsquo; philosophy that follows below
relies on direct quotations, all of which come from the Christian
writer Eusebius of Caesarea (4th c.), and on testimonies, coming from
a variety of ancient sources, such as Origen, Porphyry, Calcidius,
Macrobius, Proclus. The collection of &Eacute;. des Places used here,
in the absence of a better one, fails to distinguish between fragments
and testimonies, thus &ldquo;fr.&rdquo; in this collection and here
stands for both fragments and testimonies. Boys-Stones 2018a includes
in his collection of Middle Platonist texts all fragments and
testimonies of Numenius with English translation. Reinhardt (2023)
collects, translates and comments on the fragments of Numenius&rsquo;
<em>On the Dissension of the Academics from Plato</em>
(816&ndash;836), while Jourdan 2023, the first monograph on Numenius,
offers a collection of the fragments and testimonies of
Numenius&rsquo; work <em>On the Good</em> with French translation
(467&ndash;493).</p>
</div> 

<div id="toc"><!--Entry Contents-->
